00:06:57.964 --> 00:07:01.644
sophisticated consumer of this information, you're going to get really confused

119
00:07:01.664 --> 00:07:04.404
really fast. So how do we avoid this?

120
00:07:05.024 --> 00:07:08.824
There's definitely a lot of activity in the academic space

121
00:07:08.924 --> 00:07:10.624
to lay out kind of what

122
00:07:11.484 --> 00:07:15.144
the rules of the road should be. This is a paper that was just recently

123
00:07:15.184 --> 00:07:19.164
published last month by Peter Sassini, who presented at our session

124
00:07:19.224 --> 00:07:22.964
last year and is a great thinker in this space.

125
00:07:24.144 --> 00:07:27.604
He's talking about MCED tests here as part of a

126
00:07:27.644 --> 00:07:29.244
reaction to the recent

127
00:07:31.164 --> 00:07:34.644
alliance reference set project of the National Cancer Institute to

128
00:07:34.764 --> 00:07:35.384
compare

129
00:07:36.984 --> 00:07:40.684
MCED technologies using common reference samples.

130
00:07:41.284 --> 00:07:44.664
And he's saying, I've just highlighted some of his most important thoughts here,

131
00:07:44.784 --> 00:07:48.534
that comparison between assays should be based not

132
00:07:48.584 --> 00:07:52.504
cancer type by type for an MCED, but to the union of cancer types that

133
00:07:52.524 --> 00:07:56.424
are targeted from the test. The language we use in our working group to talk

134
00:07:56.484 --> 00:07:59.064
about that concept is the target condition.

135
00:07:59.124 --> 00:08:01.744
Is the target condition one cancer type?

136
00:08:01.823 --> 00:08:05.304
Is it selected cancer types, or is it more of a

137
00:08:05.384 --> 00:08:08.984
pan-cancer set of targets? And that

138
00:08:09.264 --> 00:08:12.754
obviously really matters for MCED, and you need to know

139
00:08:13.404 --> 00:08:15.024
what the target condition is.

140
00:08:16.384 --> 00:08:17.554
He's also saying it's not

141
00:08:18.404 --> 00:08:22.304
possible to line up sensitivity and specificity separately,

142
00:08:22.584 --> 00:08:26.564
because if you have two tests with different specificities, the sensitivity is not

143
00:08:26.584 --> 00:08:28.884
directly comparable, but we see that happen all the time.

144
00:08:29.784 --> 00:08:32.345
Lastly, he's saying, and this does sound like a pretty

145
00:08:33.764 --> 00:08:37.304
big thing to swallow, but if we're going to do this

146
00:08:37.324 --> 00:08:38.184
correctly, we need to

147
00:08:39.164 --> 00:08:42.725
present for the study population.

148
00:08:42.845 --> 00:08:43.605
We need four

149
00:08:44.504 --> 00:08:48.044
levels of stage, detailed cancer type distributions, and for the

150
00:08:48.084 --> 00:08:52.004
cancer-free individuals, we got to look at sex and five-year age group, along

151
00:08:52.044 --> 00:08:54.024
with the correction factor for racial ethnic groups.

152
00:08:54.184 --> 00:08:57.824
So this is kind of just getting at what is it going to take to really

153
00:08:58.404 --> 00:09:00.084
be apples to apples with these things.

154
00:09:01.884 --> 00:09:05.564
And I'm going to let Bree tell you a little bit about what our working group is

155
00:09:05.604 --> 00:09:07.804
