00:14:42.828 --> 00:14:45.868
Good. I have no financial relationships to disclose.

250
00:14:47.448 --> 00:14:51.117
The core of what this presentation is going to focus on is that we've been doing

251
00:14:51.228 --> 00:14:55.068
single cancer early detection tests for easily

252
00:14:55.108 --> 00:14:57.288
over 50 years, actually much longer than that.

253
00:14:57.908 --> 00:15:01.488
And as we look at these new multi-cancer early detection tests, we have a tendency

254
00:15:01.528 --> 00:15:05.138
to view them through the lens of the measurements and the

255
00:15:05.168 --> 00:15:08.748
evaluations of single cancer early detection tests.

256
00:15:09.188 --> 00:15:11.348
They have some things in common. They clearly

257
00:15:12.128 --> 00:15:15.488
place a high priority on early detection.

258
00:15:16.028 --> 00:15:17.608
We want to know how accurate the tests are.

259
00:15:18.028 --> 00:15:20.888
But the tests are fundamentally different in ways that

260
00:15:21.788 --> 00:15:25.568
make us need to think carefully about how we apply those concepts

261
00:15:25.988 --> 00:15:27.128
in a different way.

262
00:15:28.108 --> 00:15:31.888
Basically, the aim of cancer screening is to detect cancers

263
00:15:31.948 --> 00:15:33.978
or pre-cancers early in their natural history.

264
00:15:34.388 --> 00:15:38.078
If we do that, we can sometimes prevent the disease, or we can

265
00:15:38.448 --> 00:15:41.468
find it early enough to alter the natural history, and

266
00:15:42.268 --> 00:15:44.048
the patient can have a much better outcome.

267
00:15:45.068 --> 00:15:48.828
It's important to understand, though, at the core, a screening test is

268
00:15:48.928 --> 00:15:52.288
not a diagnostic test. It is not intended to diagnose

269
00:15:52.728 --> 00:15:56.648
cancer. It basically separates the many who are

270
00:15:56.688 --> 00:16:00.588
very likely not to have cancer from the small number that may and need

271
00:16:00.668 --> 00:16:01.688
further evaluation.

272
00:16:02.748 --> 00:16:04.768
The two tests actually share this in common.

273
00:16:05.908 --> 00:16:09.068
Sensitivity is the probability that a result

274
00:16:09.108 --> 00:16:13.088
will be positive when the test is applied to a person

275
00:16:13.128 --> 00:16:16.528
with cancer. Specificity is the probability that the test will be

276
00:16:16.588 --> 00:16:20.468
negative when it's applied to a person who does not have cancer.

277
00:16:20.508 --> 00:16:24.218
For convenience and practicality, these measures are defined

278
00:16:24.608 --> 00:16:28.167
and calculated within the boundaries of the screening interval.

279
00:16:28.178 --> 00:16:31.888
In other words, if these adverse events, these different events, haven't happened

280
00:16:31.908 --> 00:16:35.168
within a year or two years or 10 years, then the

281
00:16:35.228 --> 00:16:38.048
original reading is upheld.

282
00:16:38.988 --> 00:16:42.588
And there are fundamental differences between the way these tests work that

283
00:16:42.868 --> 00:16:46.008
mean that we have to think more carefully about how these measures are applied.

284
00:16:47.588 --> 00:16:51.408
So in single cancer early detection tests, test sensitivity is typically

285
00:16:51.428 --> 00:16:52.668
higher. We tend to put a very

286
00:16:53.788 --> 00:16:55.868
high bar on high test sensitivity.

287
00:16:56.648 --> 00:17:00.108
And when test sensitivity is lower, and it can be lower,

288
00:17:00.888 --> 00:17:04.548
if a test is applied on a regular basis, you can focus on what we call

289
00:17:04.668 --> 00:17:08.608
program sensitivity. That is, if we did not detect

290
00:17:08.648 --> 00:17:12.548
the test on the previous round, there's a very good chance we'll detect it on

291
00:17:12.588 --> 00:17:16.138
the subsequent round. If the cancer is relatively slow-growing,

292
00:17:16.488 --> 00:17:20.469
there's no harm. We still have a very favorable prognosis at the time

293
00:17:20.508 --> 00:17:23.888
of diagnosis. So when you compare maybe more

294
00:17:23.929 --> 00:17:27.828
expensive and more complicated tests that are done less frequently with the

295
00:17:27.908 --> 00:17:31.708
less expensive tests we want to do more frequently, we like to compare

296
00:17:31.808 --> 00:17:34.787
program sensitivity because it really levels the playing field.

297
00:17:36.308 --> 00:17:39.908
For specific cancers, sensitivity can vary by protocol.

298
00:17:40.448 --> 00:17:44.348
It can vary by technology, the program, and the operators

299
00:17:44.508 --> 00:17:48.108
in that program. Some tests are very operator-dependent, and the

300
00:17:48.168 --> 00:17:50.518
histology and host characteristics.

301
00:17:50.778 --> 00:17:54.648
So there's a lot of factors that can actually influence measures of sensitivity.

302
00:17:56.608 --> 00:18:00.428
Sensitivity can be improved by quality measures, and it can be improved by

303
00:18:00.438 --> 00:18:04.168
accepting lower specificity. It's commonly asserted

304
00:18:04.228 --> 00:18:07.668
that when specificity goes up, sensitivity goes

305
00:18:07.968 --> 00:18:11.398
down. When specificity goes down,

306
00:18:11.458 --> 00:18:14.358
sensitivity goes up, that they are inversely related.

307
00:18:14.368 --> 00:18:18.128
But that's not strictly true. When you have a test that you can

308
00:18:18.168 --> 00:18:22.052
improve its qualityAnd when it's operator dependent,

309
00:18:22.132 --> 00:18:25.612
say in interpretation, you can actually move sensitivity and

310
00:18:25.712 --> 00:18:29.412
specificity up simultaneously. Now, at the

311
00:18:29.552 --> 00:18:33.532
ragged edges of the very highest rates, yes, there's no free lunch.

312
00:18:34.012 --> 00:18:37.152
An increment in specificity is going to reduce your

313
00:18:37.592 --> 00:18:41.532
sensitivity. But they both can move up together.

314
00:18:43.552 --> 00:18:47.452
Now, in MCED tests, sensitivity is typically lower, and

315
00:18:47.492 --> 00:18:51.232
it varies by individual cancers. It is lower for early-stage disease

