496
00:29:32.252 --> 00:29:35.882
detection tests. With MCEDs, test specificity is higher.

497
00:29:36.542 --> 00:29:40.472
The predictive value at biopsy is higher than single cancer early detection

498
00:29:40.512 --> 00:29:44.452
tests. And it remains to be determined how much follow-up time

499
00:29:44.492 --> 00:29:48.202
will be required if you have a positive test without being able to do any

500
00:29:48.392 --> 00:29:52.272
cancer to determine whether or not that original test result actually

501
00:29:52.292 --> 00:29:55.852
was correct, but we do not have the tools yet to find the cancer

502
00:29:56.632 --> 00:29:58.572
through imaging or other ways.

503
00:30:00.312 --> 00:30:04.252
All right, so after more than a half-century evaluation of single cancer early

504
00:30:04.292 --> 00:30:08.132
tests, we still are learning about the nuances of how to think about sensitivity

505
00:30:08.142 --> 00:30:11.832
and specificity and what we label as false positives and

506
00:30:11.872 --> 00:30:12.292
negatives.

507
00:30:13.252 --> 00:30:17.092
MCEDs represent a potential paradigm shift in screening and

508
00:30:17.152 --> 00:30:19.582
a game changer in reducing the cancer burden.

509
00:30:20.432 --> 00:30:24.112
And similar to SCED tests, screening with an MCED test should be

510
00:30:24.212 --> 00:30:27.952
viewed as a process of information gathering rather than a

511
00:30:27.992 --> 00:30:31.622
series of discrete tests. We will face challenges in working up these

512
00:30:31.652 --> 00:30:34.512
tests. Our challenge is to meet those challenges.

513
00:30:35.652 --> 00:30:39.312
MCED performance characteristics and screening outcomes are not directly

514
00:30:39.352 --> 00:30:43.272
analogous to the measures we use for single cancer early detection tests.

515
00:30:43.832 --> 00:30:47.192
MCEDs detect multiple cancers via shared signals.

516
00:30:47.592 --> 00:30:51.532
They may detect more than one cancer signal at a time or detect a

517
00:30:51.592 --> 00:30:54.392
shared cancer signal for a cancer that is not a target of the

518
00:30:54.432 --> 00:30:58.038
test.We need to compare these tests as to how well they

519
00:30:58.088 --> 00:31:01.617
identify tissues of origin or how other

520
00:31:01.628 --> 00:31:03.778
processes for working up a positive finding.

521
00:31:05.248 --> 00:31:09.108
The performance measures and outcomes, as you heard in the introduction, need to be

522
00:31:09.148 --> 00:31:12.878
tailored and interpreted in the context of the unique characteristics of

523
00:31:12.948 --> 00:31:14.808
these tests, and we're not there yet.

524
00:31:15.788 --> 00:31:19.128
But in a world where these two tests are going to coexist,

525
00:31:19.628 --> 00:31:23.368
establishing consistent definitions for true and false positives,

526
00:31:23.788 --> 00:31:27.198
which properly should be called recall for further evaluation,

527
00:31:27.948 --> 00:31:31.588
and the tissue of origin accuracy are critical for comparing tests,

528
00:31:32.208 --> 00:31:35.448
guiding regulatory expectations, and supporting clinical

529
00:31:35.528 --> 00:31:37.188
decision-making. Thank you.

530
00:31:49.828 --> 00:31:50.508
Thanks, everybody.

531
00:31:52.348 --> 00:31:55.988
My name is Nima. I'm a radiation oncologist and a clinical researcher from

532
00:31:56.008 --> 00:31:59.648
Portland, Oregon, and my biases as a clinician will be

533
00:31:59.767 --> 00:32:01.128
readily apparent in my talk.

534
00:32:06.268 --> 00:32:06.988
Waiting on the...

535
00:32:18.648 --> 00:32:18.968
There we go.

536
00:32:26.948 --> 00:32:29.028
Sorry, I was making your job harder by moving the mouse. My bad.

537
00:32:30.608 --> 00:32:31.328
All right. So

538
00:32:32.228 --> 00:32:32.548
today,

539
00:32:33.428 --> 00:32:36.268
thank you, Bree, for tasking me with one of the more nuanced topics.

540
00:32:36.348 --> 00:32:38.468
I appreciate that. I want to focus on a

541
00:32:39.048 --> 00:32:41.858
deceptively simple question.

542
00:32:43.008 --> 00:32:46.748
That is, what exactly is the target condition in multi-cancer early

543
00:32:46.768 --> 00:32:50.688
detection tests? As Bob nicely alluded to, for single

544
00:32:50.808 --> 00:32:52.788
cancer screening, that's usually pretty obvious.

545
00:32:53.388 --> 00:32:55.368
But for MCED tests, that's really not.

546
00:32:55.408 --> 00:32:59.048
And how we answer this question has real consequences for clinicians,

547
00:32:59.148 --> 00:33:02.848
regulators, patients, payers, and developers.

548
00:33:04.188 --> 00:33:04.988
Here are my disclosures.

549
00:33:08.188 --> 00:33:11.828
So in single cancer screening, target conditions are typically defined as a

550
00:33:11.928 --> 00:33:14.888
specific disease entity and a specific use population.

551
00:33:15.808 --> 00:33:19.388
They're usually anchored to a familiar label: breast,

552
00:33:19.468 --> 00:33:22.868
cervical, colorectal, lung. Those USPSTF A and

553
00:33:22.908 --> 00:33:24.778
B labels that we're all used to.

554
00:33:25.588 --> 00:33:28.248
And these cancer screening tests have

555
00:33:30.268 --> 00:33:34.008
defined clinical workflows, confirmatory testing, and

556
00:33:34.028 --> 00:33:37.748
regulatory endpoints all around that same label.

557
00:33:37.868 --> 00:33:41.608
And that alignment is what makes single cancer screening feel intuitive

558
00:33:41.748 --> 00:33:44.028
to clinicians and straightforward for regulators.

559
00:33:46.328 --> 00:33:50.148
But MCEDs really break that traditional model, as Bob also

560
00:33:50.188 --> 00:33:54.048
alluded to. It's because these MCED tests are built on a

561
00:33:54.128 --> 00:33:57.618
shared tumor biology in the blood and not a single

562
00:33:57.728 --> 00:33:58.568
anatomic organ.

563
00:33:59.808 --> 00:34:03.668
Stakeholders still often want organ-by-organ harm-benefit evidence,

564
00:34:04.508 --> 00:34:08.247
but the underlying biology frequently behaves in clusters.

565
00:34:08.348 --> 00:34:12.028
So, traditional screening is defined by the

566
00:34:12.048 --> 00:34:15.908
tool's reach. However, MCEDs are defined by the biology's reach,

567
00:34:16.248 --> 00:34:17.968
and those are not always the same thing.

568
00:34:18.649 --> 00:34:20.728
And this is the root of the target condition problem.

569
00:34:23.828 --> 00:34:26.717
A major part of that confusion is that different stakeholders mean different things

570
00:34:26.748 --> 00:34:30.488
when they say cancer type, just as Tina and Bree alluded to, as far as

571
00:34:30.497 --> 00:34:33.089
creating a common definition in this field.

572
00:34:34.089 --> 00:34:36.188
Pathologists want biologic precision.

573
00:34:36.208 --> 00:34:39.708
They're looking at things like histology, subtype, lineage, biomarkers.

574
00:34:40.528 --> 00:34:41.928
Epidemiologists and regulators

575
00:34:44.348 --> 00:34:46.728
would want to have definitional consistency.

576
00:34:47.268 --> 00:34:50.968
They want to see a reproducible case definition that allows for fair comparison

577
00:34:50.988 --> 00:34:51.688
across studies.

578
00:34:52.629 --> 00:34:54.928
And then me as a clinician, I want management clarity.

579
00:34:55.288 --> 00:34:59.168
I want confidence that the result maps to a clear, evidence-based

580
00:34:59.268 --> 00:35:02.688
next step, and MCEDs sit at the intersection of all three of these.

581
00:35:05.268 --> 00:35:09.148
In my opinion, the target condition in MCED tests cannot be separated

582
00:35:09.258 --> 00:35:10.528
from cancer signal origin.

583
00:35:11.907 --> 00:35:15.688
For MCED tests that utilize methylation-based approaches, the biologic

584
00:35:15.708 --> 00:35:19.068
premise is that the DNA that's shed within the bloodstream has patterns that

585
00:35:19.088 --> 00:35:21.948
reflect both malignancy and tissue of origin.

586
00:35:22.668 --> 00:35:26.348
And with that methylation signature, a cancer signal origin can be

587
00:35:26.368 --> 00:35:30.088
provided to the clinician to help link detection with a predicted diagnostic

588
00:35:30.168 --> 00:35:30.588
pathway.

589
00:35:33.228 --> 00:35:36.978
I plead to the folks in this crowd right now, investigators and developers, to

590
00:35:36.988 --> 00:35:40.148
continue working on these localization efforts for the cancer signal origin.

591
00:35:40.448 --> 00:35:43.988
It's incredibly helpful for me as the end user, incredibly helpful for the

592
00:35:44.028 --> 00:35:47.108
patients as well. Detection alone is not enough.

593
00:35:47.188 --> 00:35:50.068
The field needs to keep pushing toward this localization.

594
00:35:52.708 --> 00:35:56.528
Across multiple data sets, cancer signal origin is accurate enough to be

595
00:35:56.568 --> 00:36:00.458
clinically useful as a workup diagnostic tool, a workup directing tool,

596
00:36:01.028 --> 00:36:04.148
and I myself have experience with that as well.

597
00:36:04.188 --> 00:36:08.178
The key point here is that just the PPV is not meaningful, but that

598
00:36:08.208 --> 00:36:12.048
the CSO accuracy is consistently high enough to help

599
00:36:12.128 --> 00:36:15.948
narrow the diagnostic search. And this shifts MCEDs from being

600
00:36:16.028 --> 00:36:19.768
a vague screening signal to a clinically actionable starting point.

601
00:36:24.288 --> 00:36:27.468
I think one way to think about the target condition grouping is biologic parity.

602
00:36:28.328 --> 00:36:31.968
Some CSOs reflect embryologic, molecular,

603
00:36:32.428 --> 00:36:33.468
or histologic

604
00:36:34.308 --> 00:36:37.938
relationships more so than strict organ boundaries.

605
00:36:38.908 --> 00:36:42.208
Examples of this include HPV tumors, hematologic cancers,

606
00:36:42.688 --> 00:36:46.008
neuroendocrine cancers, and soft tissue carcinomas.

607
00:36:46.888 --> 00:36:50.608
So if the biology clusters naturally, it may make more

608
00:36:50.668 --> 00:36:54.528
sense to evaluate some targets in biologic families

609
00:36:54.588 --> 00:36:56.588
rather than forcing them into rigid anatomic

610
00:36:56.648 --> 00:37:00.492
boxes.A second

611
00:37:00.532 --> 00:37:04.452
way, and in many ways, a more pragmatic approach, is grouping

612
00:37:04.492 --> 00:37:05.822
by clinical workup parity.

613
00:37:06.912 --> 00:37:10.332
Here, the target condition is defined by the diagnostic pathway it

614
00:37:10.372 --> 00:37:13.972
triggers. The important idea is that the harm of the workup may be

615
00:37:14.012 --> 00:37:17.692
relatively fixed. For example, one CT may evaluate multiple

616
00:37:17.732 --> 00:37:19.142
CSOs in a single scan,

617
00:37:19.952 --> 00:37:23.252
and in turn, the diagnostic yield rises as you consider the cluster.

618
00:37:24.292 --> 00:37:27.952
This is why pathway-based grouping may be more clinically honest than

619
00:37:28.012 --> 00:37:30.512
cancer by cancer splitting in many MCED settings.

620
00:37:33.532 --> 00:37:36.992
So how should regulators, clinicians, and payers compare these MCED technologies?

621
00:37:37.632 --> 00:37:41.412
Again, I believe not just by an aggregate sensitivity or number of cancer

622
00:37:41.492 --> 00:37:43.672
types detected, but

623
00:37:44.052 --> 00:37:47.842
comparing these tests on common units, and those

624
00:37:47.912 --> 00:37:51.032
units may be the biologic reach, CSO accuracy,

625
00:37:51.672 --> 00:37:55.152
diagnostic pathway efficiency, workup burden, or actionable yield.

626
00:37:56.012 --> 00:37:59.152
And this is all because regulators need interpretable and reproducible target

627
00:37:59.212 --> 00:38:02.992
condition definitions, clinicians and patients need confidence that the result

628
00:38:03.132 --> 00:38:06.852
maps to a workable diagnostic pathway, and payers need evidence that the

629
00:38:06.872 --> 00:38:09.132
downstream workup burden is justified by yield and value.

630
00:38:11.132 --> 00:38:13.552
So this is the part of my talk where it becomes pretty clinical.

631
00:38:13.852 --> 00:38:16.742
So I apologize for those of you in the crowd who

632
00:38:21.272 --> 00:38:21.932
potentially

633
00:38:22.792 --> 00:38:26.692
may see the bias in my talk coming in as a physician.

634
00:38:27.852 --> 00:38:31.332
The CSO is not just a navigational tool, it changes how we

635
00:38:31.412 --> 00:38:33.392
interpret indeterminate findings.

636
00:38:34.272 --> 00:38:36.392
Indeterminate findings are everywhere in medicine.

637
00:38:36.692 --> 00:38:37.952
I see them every day in my practice.

638
00:38:37.982 --> 00:38:41.872
And in an average risk patient, many of them are watched conservatively, the

639
00:38:41.992 --> 00:38:43.112
don't worry about it approach.

640
00:38:44.152 --> 00:38:48.012
But when a subtle abnormality matches the CSO

641
00:38:48.092 --> 00:38:51.782
from a positive MCED result, the post-test probability and

642
00:38:51.812 --> 00:38:55.612
malignancy changes, and that alignment can justify moving from the don't

643
00:38:55.652 --> 00:38:58.372
worry about it approach to more aggressive diagnostic action.

644
00:38:59.752 --> 00:39:02.672
And these principles have been shaped by real experience at OHSU.

645
00:39:02.952 --> 00:39:06.892
Across nearly 10,000 tested individuals and more than 100 signal-positive workups,

646
00:39:07.432 --> 00:39:11.212
our team has learned a great deal about how these MCED tests

647
00:39:11.232 --> 00:39:14.792
perform in practice and how the cancer signal origin can

648
00:39:14.832 --> 00:39:18.712
influence clinical management. And these next few cases illustrate that.

649
00:39:19.372 --> 00:39:23.292
This is a participant. Again, these next participants are all asymptomatic,

650
00:39:23.352 --> 00:39:27.122
no symptoms on presentation, receiving a multi-cancer early detection test for

651
00:39:27.192 --> 00:39:30.982
cancer screening. They had a positive test with a cancer signal origin for head and

652
00:39:31.012 --> 00:39:34.672
neck cancer. One of the initial diagnostic pathways in these

653
00:39:34.712 --> 00:39:37.032
scenarios is send these patients to our head and neck colleagues.

654
00:39:37.512 --> 00:39:41.452
They did a full workup, including nasopharyngeal laryngoscopy, all

655
00:39:41.492 --> 00:39:44.172
the way down to the larynx. No mucosal disease was seen.

656
00:39:44.692 --> 00:39:48.092
The next step in the workup was to get a CT of the neck, which revealed a

657
00:39:48.152 --> 00:39:51.212
sub-centimeter left neck lymph node identified here.

658
00:39:52.052 --> 00:39:55.552
Lymph nodes throughout the body are incredibly common, and many times we go the

659
00:39:55.652 --> 00:39:57.192
don't worry about it conservative approach.

660
00:39:57.752 --> 00:40:01.202
However, because of the signal-positive test and the CSO that matched

661
00:40:01.792 --> 00:40:04.372
this indeterminate finding in the scan,

662
00:40:05.172 --> 00:40:08.102
and because my colleagues had some

663
00:40:09.712 --> 00:40:13.392
experience working with these MCED tests, we were able to take the next step

664
00:40:13.772 --> 00:40:16.862
to do a neck dissection to further confirm this lymph node.

665
00:40:16.892 --> 00:40:19.932
This was too deep and inaccessible for FNA biopsy.

666
00:40:20.472 --> 00:40:24.412
And indeed, it returned to be an HPV positive head and neck cancer

667
00:40:24.452 --> 00:40:27.612
of unknown primary, and patient has received definitive chemoradiation.

668
00:40:28.292 --> 00:40:31.852
Again, turning indeterminate findings into aggressive action for this

669
00:40:31.892 --> 00:40:32.332
patient.

670
00:40:34.232 --> 00:40:37.892
Here's another asymptomatic patient who had a cancer signal origin for a lymphoid

671
00:40:37.932 --> 00:40:41.892
malignancy, and part of that initial workup for any lymphoma is a whole-body

672
00:40:41.992 --> 00:40:45.822
PET CT, which revealed a single FDG-avid lymph node in the

673
00:40:45.892 --> 00:40:49.772
left groin. Again, this is something, as a radiation oncologist, I see all

674
00:40:49.792 --> 00:40:53.582
the time in my practice and many times chalk it up to something reactive and

675
00:40:53.632 --> 00:40:56.452
benign. However, because it matched the CSO

676
00:40:58.252 --> 00:40:58.632
finding,

677
00:40:59.812 --> 00:41:02.852
a very skilled radiologist was able to do a core needle biopsy, ultimately

678
00:41:02.872 --> 00:41:06.752
revealing a stage one follicular lymphoma, and the patient has received curative

679
00:41:06.792 --> 00:41:07.892
low-dose radiation for that.

680
00:41:10.212 --> 00:41:14.192
This is another interesting case of a patient who many years

681
00:41:14.252 --> 00:41:17.592
ago had a gastric bypass surgery, and this will become relevant here in a little

682
00:41:17.612 --> 00:41:19.292
bit, who had a

683
00:41:20.092 --> 00:41:23.272
MCED test positive for a gastric or esophageal origin.

684
00:41:24.592 --> 00:41:28.492
We sent him to our gastroenterology colleagues. The upper endoscopy was normal.

685
00:41:28.552 --> 00:41:32.232
However, because of the gastric bypass surgery, they were unable to

686
00:41:32.272 --> 00:41:35.182
traverse and access the distal two-thirds of the stomach.

687
00:41:35.952 --> 00:41:39.342
Before deeming this patient as a false positive, we got a PET CT.

688
00:41:39.352 --> 00:41:43.232
PET CT showed some avidity within the antrum

689
00:41:43.312 --> 00:41:47.052
of the stomach, the portion that was bypassed from his surgery

690
00:41:47.092 --> 00:41:50.172
previously. And again, FDG avidity of

691
00:41:50.272 --> 00:41:53.832
gastrointestinal organs is something we see all the time in practice.

692
00:41:53.892 --> 00:41:57.872
This is a highly metabolically organ, and more cases than

693
00:41:57.912 --> 00:42:00.632
not, they are followed expectantly or ignored.

694
00:42:01.072 --> 00:42:03.212
But again, because it matched the CSO,

695
00:42:04.052 --> 00:42:08.032
we had evidence to proceed into the operating room under general

696
00:42:08.052 --> 00:42:11.752
anesthesia to perform a double balloon enteroscopy.

697
00:42:11.792 --> 00:42:15.582
This is an advanced procedure that our endoscopy colleagues performed,

698
00:42:15.652 --> 00:42:19.512
where a very long endoscope is looped into the small intestine

699
00:42:19.532 --> 00:42:21.992
and back into the bypass portion of the stomach.

700
00:42:22.572 --> 00:42:26.522
Biopsy ultimately revealing a gastric adenocarcinoma in patient receiving

701
00:42:26.572 --> 00:42:28.292
curative chemotherapy and surgery.

702
00:42:31.092 --> 00:42:34.732
This next case is clinically interesting and maybe unsettling,

703
00:42:34.872 --> 00:42:35.452
based on

704
00:42:36.552 --> 00:42:39.072
your take. This is a patient, again, who had a

705
00:42:39.972 --> 00:42:41.922
lymphoid signal origin finding.

706
00:42:43.232 --> 00:42:46.322
PET CT, again, a whole body PET CT was normal, was

707
00:42:46.372 --> 00:42:49.972
negative. No subtle abnormalities for us to chase.

708
00:42:49.992 --> 00:42:53.872
This patient was also seen by ENT because they also had a

709
00:42:53.912 --> 00:42:57.152
nasal polyp that we wanted to make sure wasn't a lymphoma. That was benign.

710
00:42:58.112 --> 00:43:01.284
One year later, they presented with throat pain.And further

711
00:43:01.324 --> 00:43:05.304
workup revealed a diffuse large B-cell lymphoma of the head and

712
00:43:05.324 --> 00:43:09.284
neck, a Stage 2 diffuse large B-cell lymphoma originating in the tonsil.

713
00:43:10.694 --> 00:43:12.454
And this case illustrates that

714
00:43:13.924 --> 00:43:17.844
even though some cases may be deemed false positive and they may be

715
00:43:17.904 --> 00:43:21.224
clinically occult on imaging, they may require

716
00:43:21.264 --> 00:43:25.104
longitudinal follow-up because some patients may actually progress with the cancer

717
00:43:25.184 --> 00:43:28.744
detected by these MCED tests. And how to identify those patients

718
00:43:28.824 --> 00:43:30.744
are way out of my wheelhouse right now.

719
00:43:33.744 --> 00:43:37.644
This last case is not a patient who had an MCED test, but I think

720
00:43:37.684 --> 00:43:39.664
it's illustrative for many reasons.

721
00:43:40.504 --> 00:43:43.064
This is a patient from our liver tumor board.

722
00:43:43.784 --> 00:43:47.584
And I had no business with this case, and I had my microphone muted, but just kind

723
00:43:47.624 --> 00:43:50.624
of thinking to myself, this is a patient who had a

724
00:43:51.364 --> 00:43:55.264
hepatocellular carcinoma found on ultrasound screening because they had high risk

725
00:43:55.304 --> 00:43:57.944
of cancer because of their cirrhosis. It was biopsy proven.

726
00:43:58.584 --> 00:44:02.164
The fantastic PCP that found this cancer was trying

727
00:44:02.224 --> 00:44:05.783
to speed up his workup as he was seeing oncology and ordered a

728
00:44:05.804 --> 00:44:09.514
PET-CT. PET-CT is not a common diagnostic workup for

729
00:44:09.524 --> 00:44:12.904
hepatocellular carcinomas, especially for well-differentiated ones.

730
00:44:12.944 --> 00:44:14.444
They just don't take up the PET tracer.

731
00:44:15.044 --> 00:44:18.374
And you can see on this PET-CT for this patient, a kind of

732
00:44:18.464 --> 00:44:21.144
heterogeneous uptake in the liver here.

733
00:44:21.174 --> 00:44:25.034
And this portion of uptake here is the duodenum, and

734
00:44:25.364 --> 00:44:27.464
just physiologic uptake in the duodenum.

735
00:44:27.484 --> 00:44:30.284
Some heterogeneity, maybe something here, maybe something here.

736
00:44:30.344 --> 00:44:32.324
But really not enough to call anything.

737
00:44:33.224 --> 00:44:36.464
When the patient came to OHSU, we knew that they needed some

738
00:44:37.244 --> 00:44:41.084
focused workup for HCC, which includes a multiphasic

739
00:44:41.164 --> 00:44:44.744
MRI. And a liver-specific

740
00:44:44.784 --> 00:44:48.704
multiphasic MRI revealed two obvious hepatic masses, quite

741
00:44:48.744 --> 00:44:51.684
large, that were pretty inapparent on the PET-CT.

742
00:44:52.324 --> 00:44:56.264
So this just, I think, drives the point home that even though you have a CSO

743
00:44:56.284 --> 00:44:59.684
and even though you've imaged the organ, you might not be

744
00:45:00.364 --> 00:45:04.344
providing the right imaging test for the patient. And the CSO really helped us.

745
00:45:05.524 --> 00:45:09.224
And I thought to myself in tumor board, if this patient had an MCED test

746
00:45:09.244 --> 00:45:12.824
without that CSO finding, I probably would've blown right through an HCC.

747
00:45:15.844 --> 00:45:19.704
So in summary, I think the real target condition as a clinician, in

748
00:45:19.764 --> 00:45:23.544
my opinion, is a clinically actionable cancer signal that's

749
00:45:23.624 --> 00:45:25.204
linked to a diagnostic pathway.

750
00:45:26.304 --> 00:45:29.944
I believe that MCED tests should not always be judged cancer subtype by subtype,

751
00:45:30.684 --> 00:45:34.244
and the true value of the cancer signal origin is its ability to change clinical

752
00:45:34.284 --> 00:45:36.614
management by turning uncertainty into action.

753
00:45:37.764 --> 00:45:41.714
And these precise target condition definitions, again, the work of

754
00:45:41.744 --> 00:45:45.314
the Blood PAC committee, are foundational for valid interpretation

755
00:45:45.344 --> 00:45:48.444
across technical, clinical, regulatory, and reimbursement stakeholders.

756
00:45:49.564 --> 00:45:53.524
Here's a picture that I took on my phone up from our medical

757
00:45:53.604 --> 00:45:55.364
center at Oregon Health &amp; Science University.

758
00:45:55.444 --> 00:45:58.644
This is the Portland Aerial Tram, transports

759
00:45:59.024 --> 00:45:59.564
patients,

760
00:46:00.864 --> 00:46:04.724
employees, such as myself, and tourists from the Willamette River up to the

761
00:46:04.764 --> 00:46:05.344
medical center.

762
00:46:06.164 --> 00:46:07.704
Please feel free to contact me. Thank you.

763
00:46:21.964 --> 00:46:25.344
Thank you so much to the organizers and an engaged audience.

764
00:46:25.544 --> 00:46:28.964
I'm very much looking forward to the panel discussion and visiting

765
00:46:29.244 --> 00:46:30.464
Portland one of these days.

766
00:46:32.464 --> 00:46:35.924
I'll be talking about implementation considerations for MCED

767
00:46:36.224 --> 00:46:40.064
and single cancer early detection tests, and you'll

768
00:46:40.104 --> 00:46:43.944
hear some of the same themes, but giving it a slightly different

769
00:46:44.024 --> 00:46:46.264
context. These are my disclosures.

770
00:46:48.344 --> 00:46:51.944
So, in the next 10 or 12 minutes, I'll frame the issues

771
00:46:52.004 --> 00:46:55.704
around generalizability, how we go from trial data to real-world

772
00:46:55.784 --> 00:46:59.144
application, and what this implies for

773
00:46:59.184 --> 00:47:01.814
implementation in different patient populations and settings.

774
00:47:02.474 --> 00:47:06.404
Strategies to address generalizability, what can we do about this, and

775
00:47:06.444 --> 00:47:07.884
then leave you with some summary points.

776
00:47:10.204 --> 00:47:13.924
So let's frame the problem. Trial populations differ

777
00:47:14.104 --> 00:47:17.784
systematically from intended screening populations.

778
00:47:19.284 --> 00:47:23.204
I'm sure that's a broad statement, but all of you will agree that,

779
00:47:23.404 --> 00:47:27.284
again, trial conditions are very different from when we

780
00:47:27.484 --> 00:47:31.124
apply it to our screening population, and that's true for most clinical trials.

781
00:47:31.154 --> 00:47:35.074
And we see some very interesting results from real-world application.

782
00:47:35.584 --> 00:47:39.454
In some cases, we see literally a flipped pattern in

783
00:47:39.484 --> 00:47:43.164
certain conditions. So these differences going from

784
00:47:43.204 --> 00:47:46.384
trials to real-world application really shape the

785
00:47:46.484 --> 00:47:49.744
benefit-harm balance. And hence, do we use the test?

786
00:47:50.164 --> 00:47:52.784
How much we use it, and

787
00:47:53.764 --> 00:47:55.564
what do we do as a follow-up for the test?

788
00:47:56.564 --> 00:47:59.004
But generalizability is what we're after.

789
00:47:59.524 --> 00:48:03.014
That's the intent of the trials as they're designed for clinical

790
00:48:03.084 --> 00:48:06.924
validation and also helps us guide implementation

791
00:48:06.984 --> 00:48:07.524
decisions.

792
00:48:09.504 --> 00:48:09.984
However,

793
00:48:10.864 --> 00:48:14.514
trial doesn't automatically mean intended screening

794
00:48:14.584 --> 00:48:18.224
population. So there's always some give and take that we have

795
00:48:18.264 --> 00:48:22.094
to adjust for. And the idea is we want to get

796
00:48:22.124 --> 00:48:25.584
them as close as possible because obviously we want our clinical

797
00:48:25.644 --> 00:48:29.444
validation to reflect what it would look like when we apply it to the

798
00:48:29.464 --> 00:48:32.344
general population and our patients from different settings.

799
00:48:32.904 --> 00:48:34.504
I see patients in three different settings.

800
00:48:34.884 --> 00:48:38.264
At the academic medical center, a very different population, much more

801
00:48:38.324 --> 00:48:41.504
educated, very few risk factors, and pretty healthy.

802
00:48:42.424 --> 00:48:45.544
I see patients at VA, a veteran population.

803
00:48:45.814 --> 00:48:46.144
Again,

804
00:48:47.064 --> 00:48:47.404
older,

805
00:48:48.324 --> 00:48:51.994
enriched with risk factors. And I also practice at a federally qualified

806
00:48:52.064 --> 00:48:55.604
healthcare center in Brooklyn, a very different population.

807
00:48:55.684 --> 00:48:58.744
Many of them, it's literally their first time that they're seeking healthcare.

808
00:48:59.424 --> 00:49:03.364
So you can see the application automatically gets very different when we think of

809
00:49:03.404 --> 00:49:06.752
the population.So again, there's direct implications for

810
00:49:06.772 --> 00:49:10.592
population-level benefits, because again, when I'm looking at my

811
00:49:10.652 --> 00:49:14.472
whole healthcare system, I want to see a population-level benefit that

812
00:49:14.512 --> 00:49:17.132
includes some of these subpopulations.

813
00:49:17.972 --> 00:49:21.912
And then this has implications for health equity, as I just alluded to, because

814
00:49:21.952 --> 00:49:25.712
we want these tests to not only be developed on all kinds of

815
00:49:25.752 --> 00:49:29.632
populations, but also be applicable and helpful the same way in

816
00:49:29.672 --> 00:49:30.892
different patient populations.

817
00:49:32.252 --> 00:49:35.592
So let's look at a few things that happen in trials,

818
00:49:36.312 --> 00:49:39.792
which make them look either better or worse than what we see in reality.

819
00:49:41.352 --> 00:49:43.892
As it was alluded to, there's often age

820
00:49:44.692 --> 00:49:48.672
enrichment. Many trials will actually supplement the trials with

821
00:49:48.832 --> 00:49:52.072
older age groups, enrich with more cancers.

822
00:49:53.052 --> 00:49:57.012
There's stage enrichment, as we commonly see with higher stage cancers

823
00:49:57.072 --> 00:50:00.952
because the signal is more easier to detect or there's more tumor shedding.

824
00:50:01.892 --> 00:50:05.852
Cancer known cases are often tossed in, again, to increase

825
00:50:06.852 --> 00:50:10.692
the diagnosis. And this leads

826
00:50:10.772 --> 00:50:14.652
to some non-representative prevalence in the trial population, which

827
00:50:14.692 --> 00:50:18.432
is not reflective necessarily of the populations that we're going to apply them to.

828
00:50:19.352 --> 00:50:23.172
And again, these things are done because otherwise the trials would be

829
00:50:23.312 --> 00:50:27.192
50,000, 60,000 individuals, would take 10s and 20s of

830
00:50:27.312 --> 00:50:31.172
years to complete. So we have to do something to

831
00:50:31.232 --> 00:50:34.252
increase that cancer signal, but then it comes with a cost.

832
00:50:35.412 --> 00:50:38.552
So the impacts of these enrichment strategies are threefold.

833
00:50:39.112 --> 00:50:42.082
One, as you can imagine, if we enrich them with

834
00:50:42.852 --> 00:50:46.812
high-risk individuals or more cancers, we essentially get an

835
00:50:46.852 --> 00:50:50.812
inflated positive predictive value because, again, it's a

836
00:50:50.872 --> 00:50:52.632
non-representative prevalence population.

837
00:50:53.552 --> 00:50:56.892
That also means there's a lower apparent false positive burden

838
00:50:57.732 --> 00:51:01.232
compared to a general population with a lower prevalence.

839
00:51:02.292 --> 00:51:06.092
So then the relevance to an asymptomatic low-prevalence

840
00:51:06.152 --> 00:51:08.592
population, such as the one I described first,

841
00:51:09.592 --> 00:51:12.432
becomes somewhat difficult to generalize.

842
00:51:14.092 --> 00:51:16.572
So I'll give you some examples, and again, there's many.

843
00:51:17.632 --> 00:51:21.332
So this was the first. This is a stool-based test, not a

844
00:51:21.372 --> 00:51:24.572
blood-based test. This is the Cologuard test that we currently use,

845
00:51:24.812 --> 00:51:26.262
FDA-approved, Medicare-approved,

846
00:51:27.452 --> 00:51:29.492
and fully commercialized for the last 10 years.

847
00:51:29.872 --> 00:51:30.922
This was the pivotal study,

848
00:51:31.932 --> 00:51:32.932
very ahead of its time,

849
00:51:34.552 --> 00:51:38.412
12 years ago now. And even this trial, and

850
00:51:38.472 --> 00:51:42.432
this is the trial based on which the test got both FDA and Medicare approval

851
00:51:42.532 --> 00:51:46.292
at the same time, which is unheard of for any other test,

852
00:51:46.652 --> 00:51:48.272
and no test has since been able to do that.

853
00:51:48.912 --> 00:51:50.032
Even this trial

854
00:51:50.892 --> 00:51:53.992
enrolled, and this was almost 10,000 individuals across the US.

855
00:51:54.512 --> 00:51:58.412
Enrollment was weighted towards persons 65 years of age or older

856
00:51:58.452 --> 00:52:02.092
in order to increase the prevalence of cancer. So you see this very commonly.

857
00:52:02.172 --> 00:52:06.012
It was just one line embedded in the methods, and I don't even think people in the

858
00:52:06.072 --> 00:52:09.192
field actually know that this was done or what implications it

859
00:52:09.292 --> 00:52:12.852
has. So clearly, in these next 12 years, we've had the

860
00:52:12.912 --> 00:52:13.982
opportunity to study

861
00:52:15.112 --> 00:52:18.712
the performance at a population level, and that may not

862
00:52:18.732 --> 00:52:22.492
necessarily be the same as what we saw in this trial, and you could suspect

863
00:52:22.512 --> 00:52:22.892
why.

864
00:52:24.352 --> 00:52:28.212
On the converse, trial population may be at lower risk

865
00:52:28.332 --> 00:52:30.832
for cancer than your intended use population.

866
00:52:31.532 --> 00:52:34.772
And that's because if you think about a clinical validation study

867
00:52:35.452 --> 00:52:39.232
where we ask asymptomatic individuals without any

868
00:52:39.252 --> 00:52:42.992
known cancers to enroll in the study, and that's what we enroll,

869
00:52:43.621 --> 00:52:45.232
there's a healthy volunteer bias.

870
00:52:45.281 --> 00:52:47.492
We already know they don't have any existing cancers.

871
00:52:48.132 --> 00:52:49.432
There's also a selection bias.

872
00:52:50.292 --> 00:52:53.892
People that sign up generally are motivated, they're healthy, their lifestyles are

873
00:52:53.932 --> 00:52:56.792
healthier, and their baseline cancer risk is lower.

874
00:52:56.832 --> 00:52:59.061
They tend to be non-smokers, mostly women,

875
00:53:00.012 --> 00:53:03.972
and just healthy overall. So we could actually, we think we're

876
00:53:04.052 --> 00:53:04.572
enrolling

877
00:53:06.292 --> 00:53:09.992
an intended use population, but we could actually end up enrolling a

878
00:53:10.172 --> 00:53:12.112
lower risk population.

879
00:53:12.952 --> 00:53:16.692
And this was apparent. So we are part of the NCI-funded

880
00:53:16.752 --> 00:53:19.252
consortium called Early Detection Research Network.

881
00:53:19.712 --> 00:53:23.552
It's a prospective multi-center study, and we collect

882
00:53:23.992 --> 00:53:27.892
blood, stool, and other biospecimens from average-risk individuals to

883
00:53:27.972 --> 00:53:31.872
validate different cancers. In 29 geographically

884
00:53:31.932 --> 00:53:35.892
dispersed study sites, very carefully selected to represent, we think,

885
00:53:35.952 --> 00:53:39.672
generalizability in different populations across the US, Canada, and Germany.

886
00:53:40.472 --> 00:53:40.782
And,

887
00:53:41.812 --> 00:53:45.572
we published, and this consortium has been going on for about 15 years.

888
00:53:45.672 --> 00:53:48.552
We published our results mainly for colorectal cancer,

889
00:53:49.272 --> 00:53:52.872
and we had 10 cancers in 5,291

890
00:53:53.352 --> 00:53:54.572
asymptomatic individuals.

891
00:53:55.742 --> 00:53:59.572
So the prevalence rate was 0.2%. If you look at SEER,

892
00:54:00.392 --> 00:54:03.922
the prevalence rate of colorectal cancer in the US population is

893
00:54:04.152 --> 00:54:08.092
0.7% to 1%. So you can see we were very, very under

894
00:54:08.192 --> 00:54:11.872
target compared to SEER. And SEER is not average

895
00:54:11.972 --> 00:54:15.812
risk or intended use because SEER consists of

896
00:54:15.892 --> 00:54:19.392
a mixed bag. It has people that are, at any time, they're probably

897
00:54:19.432 --> 00:54:20.032
symptomatic.

898
00:54:20.852 --> 00:54:22.932
They probably have family histories.

899
00:54:22.972 --> 00:54:26.742
There's probably some asymptomatic, but they may have variable risk factors.

900
00:54:27.022 --> 00:54:30.802
So that's not the population that we pick when we do these

901
00:54:30.812 --> 00:54:34.032
clinical studies. But obviously, we're not going to take all comers.

902
00:54:34.052 --> 00:54:37.192
We're going to take people without cancers that don't have symptoms.

903
00:54:37.872 --> 00:54:41.032
So you see where it can actually mislead

904
00:54:42.232 --> 00:54:44.092
the prevalence at the population level.

905
00:54:45.072 --> 00:54:46.852
All right. So how can we overcome this?

906
00:54:46.952 --> 00:54:50.912
So some ways to enhance generalizability, and again, I hope we can continue

907
00:54:50.952 --> 00:54:53.172
this in our discussion because there's no one perfect

908
00:54:53.252 --> 00:54:57.144
answer.A fairly straightforward

909
00:54:57.184 --> 00:55:00.484
approach is age and sex adjustment to the US census

910
00:55:00.564 --> 00:55:03.984
population. So this at least gets at the age and sex

911
00:55:04.024 --> 00:55:07.784
distribution because we said cancers are increase in

912
00:55:07.824 --> 00:55:11.664
prevalence with age. Age continues to be the strongest risk factors

913
00:55:11.744 --> 00:55:14.404
for many cancers, including colorectal cancers.

914
00:55:15.544 --> 00:55:18.844
So in the PREEMPT study, which is the clinical

915
00:55:18.924 --> 00:55:22.724
validation of the Freenome test, SimpleScreen, the blood

916
00:55:22.784 --> 00:55:24.084
test for colorectal cancer,

917
00:55:25.624 --> 00:55:29.064
very recently, after publishing that study, we actually did

918
00:55:29.284 --> 00:55:33.044
apply age and sex adjustment, just to show how different it

919
00:55:33.084 --> 00:55:36.374
was. So remind you, the study enrolled almost 50,000

920
00:55:36.404 --> 00:55:39.554
individuals. The clinical validation cohort was

921
00:55:39.744 --> 00:55:40.904
27,000.

922
00:55:41.824 --> 00:55:45.624
You would think at 27,000 individuals, any

923
00:55:45.664 --> 00:55:48.184
differences would wash out. Actually, that's not true.

924
00:55:48.684 --> 00:55:52.534
So in this graph, you see the PREEMPT CRC population

925
00:55:52.544 --> 00:55:56.324
from 201 centers in the US, with great pains

926
00:55:56.384 --> 00:55:58.444
taken to enhance generalizability.

927
00:55:58.744 --> 00:56:02.664
You can see how it stacks up to the US population for age and sex distribution.

928
00:56:03.204 --> 00:56:06.984
So clearly, we had more 50 to 54-year-olds in PREEMPT compared to the

929
00:56:07.044 --> 00:56:07.924
US population,

930
00:56:09.144 --> 00:56:13.104
and then fewer older than 75 individuals.

931
00:56:13.484 --> 00:56:17.084
We also had more women. Again, that healthy volunteer bias

932
00:56:17.364 --> 00:56:21.214
comes in than the US population. So we adjusted it, and then we said,

933
00:56:21.304 --> 00:56:23.564
"Okay, how does the performance of the test change?"

934
00:56:24.524 --> 00:56:26.564
So this is how the test performance changed.

935
00:56:26.984 --> 00:56:30.944
So, in the first column, you see the performance

936
00:56:31.004 --> 00:56:34.584
of the test original without unadjusted, what we reported

937
00:56:35.024 --> 00:56:38.964
in our JAMA paper. And then in the last column, you see after

938
00:56:39.004 --> 00:56:39.324
this

939
00:56:40.244 --> 00:56:44.044
age and sex adjustment. So you can see everything moves a little bit, and

940
00:56:44.084 --> 00:56:47.484
that's because the population kind of moves towards

941
00:56:47.924 --> 00:56:51.904
older and male. So the overall CRC sensitivity

942
00:56:52.024 --> 00:56:55.964
actually goes up from 79.2 to 81.1, which at

943
00:56:56.464 --> 00:57:00.174
27,000 plus individuals is a change.

944
00:57:00.704 --> 00:57:01.584
The stage one

945
00:57:03.244 --> 00:57:07.124
CRC sensitivity goes up from 57 to 63%,

946
00:57:08.144 --> 00:57:11.164
and then the specificity actually goes down a little bit from

947
00:57:11.324 --> 00:57:13.434
91.5% to 90%.

948
00:57:14.264 --> 00:57:17.824
Sensitivity for advanced precursor lesion also goes up from

949
00:57:17.844 --> 00:57:21.624
12.5% to 13.7%. So you can see

950
00:57:21.684 --> 00:57:25.604
this adjustment does make a difference, and if all the tests

951
00:57:25.724 --> 00:57:29.144
did similar adjustments, at least we'd have a little bit of a

952
00:57:29.584 --> 00:57:32.304
apples-to-apples comparison, but there's more nuance here.

953
00:57:33.424 --> 00:57:37.324
And the nuance is this: so, age and sex is one thing, but

954
00:57:37.364 --> 00:57:41.284
it's very crude. Obviously, we'd love to adjust by every

955
00:57:41.404 --> 00:57:42.024
other factor,

956
00:57:42.904 --> 00:57:46.704
such as you just heard, size of the tumor correlates with how much

957
00:57:46.744 --> 00:57:50.354
it's shed. So not all stage one cancers are created equal.

958
00:57:50.774 --> 00:57:53.644
Not all APLs are created equal. So

959
00:57:53.684 --> 00:57:57.513
the distribution of those different categories within that

960
00:57:57.604 --> 00:57:59.144
stage actually make a difference.

961
00:57:59.624 --> 00:58:03.464
So should we also adjust for size and

962
00:58:03.684 --> 00:58:05.044
perhaps location of cancer?

963
00:58:05.884 --> 00:58:09.404
Perhaps, there's a difference in detection by where the cancer is

964
00:58:09.444 --> 00:58:09.984
located,

965
00:58:10.784 --> 00:58:14.464
which again, is a daunting task, but you can see where the

966
00:58:14.504 --> 00:58:18.364
heterogeneity might come in between different studies and between trial

967
00:58:18.444 --> 00:58:20.244
data and real-world applications.

968
00:58:21.884 --> 00:58:25.584
This advanced precursor lesion, we've created this catchall bucket,

969
00:58:26.064 --> 00:58:29.724
and not every category we throw in there is created equal.

970
00:58:30.233 --> 00:58:33.804
So for instance, advanced adenomas with high-grade dysplasia probably

971
00:58:33.864 --> 00:58:37.704
represent the most important lesion in this advanced precursor lesion group.

972
00:58:39.004 --> 00:58:42.474
It doesn't carry the same risk of cancer as

973
00:58:42.944 --> 00:58:46.564
another category in the APL bucket is 5 to 10 non-advanced

974
00:58:46.604 --> 00:58:50.484
adenomas. So frequency doesn't equal histology and so

975
00:58:50.584 --> 00:58:54.064
forth. There's several other categories in there, such as villous histology,

976
00:58:54.164 --> 00:58:57.564
sessile serrated lesions, and they're all very different.

977
00:58:57.764 --> 00:59:01.484
We like to lump them, but essentially, they're very different.

978
00:59:01.544 --> 00:59:05.344
So what happens when in a trial you have a certain distribution, but then when you

979
00:59:05.384 --> 00:59:09.124
